Subject:    <a href="?t=95837888800022&r=1&w=2">leading digits in domain names</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837784200018&r=1&w=2">mark () cbpavo ! mis ! oh ! att ! com (Mark Horton)</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198704">1987-04-22 12:18:46</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926844&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926844&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

It has been pointed out that the RFCs specify that domain names must
begin with a letter, not a digit.  Not knowing this, we've registered
a domain name 3Com.COM, which has been in the tables for about 6 months.
No problems arose, until someone poking around in the database happened
to notice it and pointed it out.

I asked the NIC whether we should change the RFC or change the domain
name.  (Obviously, we'd prefer 3Com to keep their domain name, it's a
much better fit with the name of the company, and they've been using
the name.)  The answer wasn't clear.  Apparently the original motivation
for disallowing leading digits was to make it easy to recognize whether
a string is a host name or a numeric IP address like 192.11.2.1.  (4.2BSD
doesn't have any trouble with this, but some other systems might.)  This
only matters in the context of a host name, not a domain name.  3Com is
on UUCP, not on the Internet, so nobody is going to telnet to them.  It
only matters within the context of MX mail.

It was suggested that we should ask this list.  Have you noticed any
problems due to 3Com.COM being in the tables?  Do you expect any?  If
you do have a problem, how serious is it?  Is it worthwhile to uproot
an existing domain name, for example?  Or should we just have it apply
to future domain registrations?

Thanks,

	Mark Horton
	mark@stargate.com

